POL107H1-F-20215.courseTitle: What Went Wrong? A Post Mortem of Political Disasters, Catastrophic Policy Failures, and Epic Marches of Folly
POL107H1-F-20215.courseDescription: Why do individuals, groups, and societies make repeated, and often easily predictable mistakes? Why do they persist in courses of action that produce disastrous results? Why is it that in the political world good intentions are insufficient to ensure good results? This course employs the political science analytical toolkit to answer these questions and examines an array avoidable disasters, from the local to the international.
POL107H1-F-20215.exclusion: POL486H1 (Topics in International Politics I: What Went Wrong? A Post Mortem of Political Disasters, Policy Failures and Marches of Folly), offered in Winter 2019 and Winter 2020; POL487H1 (Topics in International Politics II: What Went Wrong? A Post Mortem of Political Disasters, Catastrophic Policy Failures), offered in Winter 2018

POL200Y1-Y-20215.courseTitle: Political Theory: Visions of the Just/Good Society
POL200Y1-Y-20215.courseDescription: A selective presentation of critical encounters between philosophy and politics, dedicated to the quest for articulation and founding of the just/good society. Among the theorists examined are Plato, Aristotle, Machiavelli, Hobbes and Locke.
POL200Y1-Y-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures will be delivered online synchronous.
  • Recordings of lectures will also be available for students to view asynchronously.
  • Tutorials will be available only as online synchronous at their scheduled times.
  • Students will be expected to watch asynchronous lecture videos prior to class meetings when indicated.
  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online activities.
POL200Y1-Y-20215.breadthCategories: Society and its Institutions (3), Thought, Belief and Behaviour (2)

POL201H1-F-20215.courseDescription: This course offers an introduction to the history and politics of economic and political development, starting with the Industrial Revolution and then turning to a critical analysis of the politics of economic growth, international trade, debt, state intervention, protectionism, and neo-liberalism in the global periphery, including Africa, Asia, and Latin America.
POL201H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures and tutorials will be delivered online synchronously per the meeting schedules.
  • All the planned lectures are posted and available on Quercus.
  • Students are encouraged to read required readings before class.
  • Students are required to have a computer with a microphone.
  • Camera is recommended in order to participate in online tutorials and discussion but not mandatory.

POL208H1-F-20215.courseDescription: This introductory course examines some key themes and issues in global politics, including interstate war, human rights, international institutions, and the evolution of the global order.
POL208H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures will be pre-recorded and delivered online asynchronously.
  • Students will be expected to do readings and listen to lectures before tutorial meetings.
  • Online class discussions will be held during the scheduled lecture meeting times to discuss topics in the lectures and to assist students with course material.
  • Tutorials will be held during the scheduled meeting times and delivered online synchronously.
  • Students require a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online tutorials and lectures.

POL214H1-F-20215.courseDescription: An introduction to the study of Canadian government. Topics include institutions of governance: the constitution, machinery of government, charter of rights and freedom, and the electoral system.
POL214H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures will be delivered online synchronously and recordings will be available for students to view asynchronously.
  • Tutorials will be available only as online synchronous, at their scheduled times.
  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online activities.

POL222H1-F-20215.courseDescription: Introduces the foundations of quantitative empirical research methods - increasingly popular and important part of political science research and public policy debates - to enable you to interpret and evaluate the results of the studies that employ these methods. Topics include scientific study of politics, empirical research designs, and regression analysis.
POL222H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures are live-streamed and recorded, permitting synchronous delivery and asynchronous attendance.
  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online tutorials.

POL232H1-S-20215.courseDescription: Building up on POL222H1, students will continue to build theoretical foundations of quantitative empirical research, such as probability theory and statistical inference. They will also learn the basic use of statistical software and have become able to conduct a basic data analysis by themselves by the end of semester.
POL232H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Students will receive zoom link beforehand to attend each scheduled class and tutorial.
  • Summary of the lecture slides and notes will be uploaded on Quercus after each lecture.
  • Students are expected to have internet access, webcam, headphone and/or speakers for this course.

POL299Y1-Y-20215.courseDescription: Credit course for supervised participation in faculty research project. Details at http://www.artsci.utoronto.ca/current/course/rop. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.

POL301Y1-Y-20215.courseDescription: The continuing relevance of pre-colonial Africa; the nature and legacy of colonial rule; African nationalism and the consolidation of power in the newly-independent states; government, party and the people; the role of the military; national integration; dependency and neo-colonialism; socialism and development; democracy and human rights.
POL301Y1-Y-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures will be delivered online synchronously per the meeting schedule.
  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate.

POL302Y1-F-20215.courseDescription: This course explores Chinas efforts to construct a modern and effective political order in the face of powerful demographic and revolutionary challenges. The clash between competing ideologies, political and social movements and institutional alternatives in the context of rapid social and economic change are analyzed.
POL302Y1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions: • Lectures will be delivered online synchronously per the meeting schedule.

POL317H1-F-20215.courseDescription: Draws from the major theoretical traditions in public policy and policymaking of the advanced industrial world, and applies these theories in understanding the developing world context and the new challenges of global change.
POL317H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate.
  • Lectures are live-streamed and recorded, permitting synchronous delivery and asynchronous attendance.

POL320Y1-Y-20215.courseDescription: The development of political thought from the Enlightenment and through the 19th century; implications for political thought in the 20th century. Democratic and anti-democratic tendencies.
POL320Y1-Y-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures will also be available to watch asynchronously for up to 1 week after recording
  • Tutorial are synchronous only
  • Students must watch lectures before tutorials
  • Students must have a microphone in order to participate in online activities.
  • A camera is recommended, but not required.

POL326Y1-F-20215.courseDescription: The foreign policy of the United States: tradition and context of American decision-making, the process by which it is formulated, application to a number of specific regions and problems in the world.
POL326Y1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions: • Lectures are live-streamed and recorded, permitting synchronous delivery and asynchronous attendance.

POL340Y1-Y-20215.courseDescription: International law as an instrument of conflict resolution. Recognition, sovereign immunity, subjects of international law, jurisdiction.
POL340Y1-Y-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures will be delivered asynchronously.
  • Instructor will hold regularly scheduled (but optional) meet-ups where students can ask questions, and course material will be related to real-world events.
  • Students are expected to do readings, and watch video and audio content and online lectures before meet-ups.

POL363H1-F-20215.courseDescription: This course introduces students to Canadian political development an approach that shows how attention to history can illuminate and explain patterns of Canadian politics. The course introduces students to core theories and tools of a developmental approach, then applies this approach to key moments, contestations, and institutions in Canadian politics.
POL363H1-F-20215.exclusion: POL382H1 (Topics in Canadian Politics: Canadian Political Development), offered in Winter 2018, Winter 2019
POL363H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures will be pre-recorded and delivered online asynchronously.
  • Online class discussions will be held during the scheduled meeting times to discuss topics in the lectures and to assist students with course material.
  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online discussions.

POL373H1-F-20215.courseDescription: Emotions are central to political life but have often been marginalized in political theory. This course explores various ways in which emotions are relevant to political theory and examines a number of contemporary debates around the new possibilities in bringing a positive consideration of the emotions back into political theory.
POL373H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures and discussion will be delivered online synchronously and recorded per the meeting schedule.
  • Participation is a key component of the course which will make consistent asynchronous access a hindrance to good performance in the course.

POL377H1-F-20215.courseDescription: An introduction to the field of comparative politics. Content in any given year depends on instructor.
POL377H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures will be held synchronously and recorded to watch asynchronously.
  • Students will be expected to watch films prior to class meetings.
  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to
    participate in online activities.

POL377H1-S-20215.courseDescription: An introduction to the field of comparative politics. Content in any given year depends on instructor.
POL377H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions:

  • Students will be expected to watch movies/documentaries prior to class meetings.
  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to
    participate in online activities.

POL378H1-S-20215.courseDescription: An introduction to the field of comparative politics. Content in any given year depends on instructor.
POL378H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions:

  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate in online seminar discussions.
  • Students are expected to complete all readings and review syllabus material prior to the attendance of lectures and seminars in order to participate fully.

POL379H1-S-20215.courseDescription: An introduction to the field of comparative politics. Content in any given year depends on instructor.
POL379H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions:
Lectures will either be pre-recorded and/or recorded with an [optional] live audience via BB Collaborate on Quercus. 

Once a week, there will be a live session for about an hour to highlight & discuss key points from the week's pre-recorded lecture. Once a week there will also be a live, online discussion, but students can alternatively participate online using discussion forums. These discussions may cover readings, films or podcasts relevant to class.

POL380H1-S-20215.courseDescription: Content in any given year depends on instructor.
POL380H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures will be delivered online synchronously per the meeting schedule.
  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera to participate in the in-class discussion.
  • Lectures will also be recorded to accommodate students that cannot join synchronously.

POL382H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions: • Lectures will be recorded and uploaded for asynchronous viewing.

POL417Y1-Y-20215.courseDescription: The countries of Africa, Asia, Latin America, and the Middle East; their impact on the international system, and the external and internal factors that influence their international behaviour, with particular focus on civil wars.
POL417Y1-Y-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Seminar will be delivered online synchronously per the meeting schedule.
  • Students are required to have a computer with a microphone and camera.
  • Camera is mandatory given that the seminar is based on the presentations and discussions.

POL431Y1-F-20215.courseTitle: Politics and Society in Contemporary China
POL431Y1-F-20215.courseDescription: Issues and themes in China's modernization effort with emphasis on 20th century social, political and economic developments.
POL431Y1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions: • Seminar to be delivered online synchronously per the meeting schedule.

POL447H1-F-20215.courseDescription: The course explores the rise, evolution, and performance of the dominant neoliberal approach to development and poverty reduction. It also assesses the feasibility and efficacy of alternative development strategies. Case studies are drawn from Latin America, Asia, and Africa.
POL447H1-F-20215.deliveryInstructions:
• Lectures will be delivered online synchronously per the meeting schedule.
  • It is recommended that students have a computer with a microphone and camera in order to participate.

POL486H1-S-20215.courseDescription: For advanced students of international relations. Various topics are taken up each year, the content of which depends on the instructor.
POL486H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions:

  • Learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule.
  • Students may watch/listen to lectures and other class material on their own schedule.

POL487H1-S-20215.courseDescription: For advanced students of international relations. Various topics are taken up each year, the content of which depends on the instructor.
POL487H1-S-20215.deliveryInstructions:
